## Migration: `BackgroundProcessor` → .NET 8

### Patterns Identified

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `while (_running)` + `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| **ThreadAbortException as control flow** | `catch` block calls `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| **Thread.ResetAbort** | Prevents rethrow so `finally` runs cleanly | Remove — `OperationCanceledException` doesn't auto-rethrow |
| **Blocking call interruption** | `GetNextItem()` may block | Must accept `CancellationToken` to unblock |

### Why This Can't Just Compile on .NET 8

- `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — it does **nothing** useful.
- `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown by the runtime — the catch block is dead code.
- `Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`.
- If `GetNextItem()` blocks indefinitely, setting `_running = false` won't wake it — `Stop()` hangs.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass the token so blocking calls can be interrupted
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work (moved from ThreadAbortException catch)
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop — replaces Thread.ResetAbort + finally flow
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        // Signal cooperative cancellation (replaces Thread.Abort)
        _cts.Cancel();

        // Wait with a timeout instead of Thread.Sleep + Abort
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't stop in time — log a warning.
            // In cooperative cancellation there is no force-kill equivalent.
            // If this happens, GetNextItem/ProcessItem isn't checking the token.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

---

### Key Changes Summary

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs; a bool can't wake a blocked thread |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal instead of forcible injection |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` guard avoids catching unrelated OCEs |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `break` | `OperationCanceledException` doesn't auto-rethrow — just exit the loop |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` then abort | `_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2))` | Non-spinning wait; no force-kill fallback |
| No disposal | `IDisposable` | `CancellationTokenSource` must be disposed to avoid timer/callback leaks |

### Critical: You Must Update `GetNextItem`

The token **must** be threaded into any blocking call, otherwise cancellation won't take effect until the call returns on its own:

```csharp
// If using a BlockingCollection<T>:
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException on cancel
}

// If using a custom wait:
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    // Replace: _event.WaitOne();
    WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { _event, token.WaitHandle });
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    return DequeueItem();
}
```

### Pitfalls to Watch

1. **Token not passed through the call chain** — If `ProcessItem()` does long-running work, pass the token there too and call `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints.
2. **`Thread.Sleep` in other code** — Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` so cancellation wakes it immediately.
3. **No force-kill exists** — If `GetNextItem` calls unmodifiable code that blocks forever, the only escape hatch is moving that work to a **child process** and using `Process.Kill`.
4. **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** — The `break` above is intentional (top-level loop exit). Deeper in the call chain, let it propagate.
